<h1><b>Photo Essay: Photography for Publishing</b></h1>
<body>
<img 
src="August 30, 2014.JPG" alt="Madeline Shawl">
<p>I started with a compact point-and-shoot digital camera, but I wasn't satisfied with the results.</p>
<img
src="March 17, 2016.JPG" alt="Swamp Selfie" width=75%>
<p>So I bought a mirrorless interchangeable lens camera with full manual capabilities, and I took a year-long email photography course to learn how to use it.</p>
<img
src=https://photos.app.goo.gl/hYzzhCqVbmYi4Bz78 alt=Shawl on a brick wall width=75%>
<p>I started to develop an eye for finding the right background scenery for each of my knit designs.</p>
<img
src=https://photos.app.goo.gl/LjDSEpKhsPvEyvib7 alt=Lightning Shawl width=75%>
<p>I bought a prime portrait lens, and then another, and experimented with blurred backgrounds and <i>bokeh</i>.</p>
<img
src=https://photos.app.goo.gl/EMu2s8ag9wdhx5Mk6 alt=Can Can Shawl width=75%>
<p>I used my past modeling experience to show off my knit creations</p>
<img
src=https://photos.app.goo.gl/1WLw4ZV5ppbKxX54A alt=Linden Street Pullover width=75%>
<p>I scouted locations to find the best backgrounds to match my knitwear, and I watched the weather for the perfect, slightly overcast conditions.</p>
<img
src=https://photos.app.goo.gl/A4EsuYK8AoHqyB3w5 alt=Augusta width=75%>
<p>With practice, I was able to consistently achieve the results I wanted.</p>
<img
src=https://images4-a.ravelrycache.com/uploads/kephrenknitting/867020531/IMG_1606_medium2.png alt=Dappled Sky Pullover width=75%>
<p>What will the next step in my digital photography journey be?</p>
<a href=https://kephrenpritchett.com>
<img src=https://kephrenpritchett.files.wordpress.com/2024/01/img_0970.png alt=letter blocks in black and white width=75%>
<p>Find out on my website!</p>
</a>
